en_6952090_0	The Central Bank of Sri Lanka notes that banks and non-banking financial institutions are required to submit their preliminary proposals on the Consolidation Plan by March 31, 2014.
en_6952090_1	Assistant Governor of the Central Banks of Sri Lanka, C.J.G. Siriwardena says that the consolidation process will not, in any way, affect the general publicâ€™s current transactions and deposits with the banks and finance companies, with whom they are presently transacting.
en_6952090_2	A master plan on the consolidation of the financial sector to create a stable financial sector with strong and dynamic financial institutions in order to steer Sri Lanka towards the economic goals set for 2016 and beyond, were proposed in the recent budget.
en_6952090_3	Accordingly, the Central of Sri Lanka set out a road made for 2014 and beyond and has already commenced its preliminary process.
en_6952090_4	Thereby, banks and non-banking financial institutions will be consolidated in different ways.
en_6952090_5	Banks and non-banking financial institutions that will be consolidated will be decided by the Central Bank of Sri Lanka and the proposed plans need to be forwarded to the CBSL for approval.
en_6952090_6	In addition, the Central Bank requested all banks, NBFIs and others who are involved in the process to continue a close dialogue with the Central Bank and obtain guidance if the need arises.
en_6952090_7	In this regard, the members of the special unit headed by the Assistant Governor were introduced to the banks and NBFIs to ease the process.
en_6952090_8	Assistant Governor of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka C.J.G.Siriwardena said that currently 58 banks and twenty one banking financial institutions are registered with the Central Bank.
en_6952090_9	Siriwardena added that certain institutions have a stable monetary foundation while others are not in a position to face a financial crisis.
en_6952090_10	He added that the consolidation effort will ensure the creation of a strong and sound monetary system.
en_6952090_11	The Central Banks of Sri Lanka added that steps will be taken against those institutions that do not cooperate with the effort.
